associated_structures: viral genome,s protein,n protein,m protein,e protein
text_description: The viral genome is about 30 kb long and its 3’ end consists of genes encoding structural proteins. S: Spike protein; E: Envelope protein; M: Membrane protein; N: Nucleocapsid protein.
ref: Dongwan Kim, Joo-Yeon Lee, Jeong-Sun Yang, Jun Won Kim, V. Narry Kim, Hyeshik Chang (2020). The Architecture of SARS-CoV-2 Transcriptome, Cell 181(4), 914-921.e10. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2020.04.011.

text_description: There are also accessory protein genes present at the 3' end of the viral genome. Only genes encoding structural proteins are shown here for simplicity.

associated_structures: rna,sub-genomic rna,negative sub-genomic rna,negative sense rna
text_description: Gene at the 3' end are transcribed into a nested set of sub-genomic RNAs. The first set of sub-genomic RNAs are negative sense RNAs.
ref: Sola, I., Almazán, F., Zúñiga, S., & Enjuanes, L. (2015). Continuous and Discontinuous RNA Synthesis in Coronaviruses. Annual review of virology, 2(1), 265–288. https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-virology-100114-055218

text_description: The negative sense RNAs are then copied into positive sense RNAs that serve as messenger RNA templates for the translation of structural proteins.
The leader sequence that is present at the 5’ end of the genomic RNA is copied into each subgenomic RNA.

The TRSs are present at the junctions between each open reading frame of genes encoding structural and accessory proteins (TRS-B), as well as in the leader sequence at the 5’ end of the genomic RNA (TRS-L).
ref: Sola, I., Almazán, F., Zúñiga, S., & Enjuanes, L. (2015). Continuous and Discontinuous RNA Synthesis in Coronaviruses. Annual review of virology, 2(1), 265–288. https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-virology-100114-055218

text_description: The process of discontinuous RNA Synthesis.
